I went to Bergen just after 6am. They had just opened. I had a toasted salt bagel with lox, cream cheese, capers, red onions, and a light and sweet coffee. It was good but not worth $16. Despite the crazy price, I would still choose Bergen over the Dunkin Donuts across the street. When in New York...

I got challah bread but I had asked the salesman is it fresh and he replied that it was. I went home that night and cut a piece of the $5 challah bread. Get your act together guys. This is not the Bergen of old before the building was re-built. Whole Wheat Everything, Toasted, cream cheese. Open the bag, not whole wheat, not toasted. Two people in the store and can't have simple straightforward communication. Worst off, the person taking my order was distracted with a task, so the cashier asked me what I ordered (I hadn't fully yet) and then she comes back sees me talking with the cashier and is annoyed... I didn't engage her, she engaged me, what am I suppose to do? Ignore her, I said "she's taking my order".  The whole set up is completely bizarre and poorly designed, why do I have to repeat my order anyway? Why isn't there a ticket system like *every where else in the food service industry*. You can't see the cream cheese selection until after you choose a bagel because they have the salad bar at the beginning of the line... Why? Terrible design choices and smug staff, except the manager, he seems alright but poorly staffed.
